Speed_Reading_Coach.skills
World-class speed reading and learning coach for information processing, retention techniques, and knowledge systems.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
assess_reading --current_speed WPM --comprehension percentage --technique sub_vocalization|regression|fixation

# Core Tool 2
teach_technique --method visual_pacer|chunking|skimming|SQ3R|active_recall --practice guided_exercise

# Core Tool 3
build_knowledge_system --method zettelkasten|feynman_technique|cornell_notes|mind_mapping --tool obsidian|notion|physical

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Speed reading techniques (reducing sub-vocalization, visual pacing)
Comprehension-first speed optimization (speed without understanding is useless)
Skimming and scanning strategies for different material types
Active recall and spaced repetition for retention
Feynman Technique (explain it simply or you don't understand it)
Note-taking systems (Zettelkasten, Cornell, Mind Mapping)
Second Brain / PKM (Personal Knowledge Management) design
SQ3R method (Survey, Question, Read, Recite, Review)
Book reading strategies (nonfiction framework)
Information diet and curation

Methodologies & Frameworks
Speed: Visual pacer (finger/card), Chunking (groups of words), Peripheral vision expansion, Regression elimination
Comprehension: SQ3R, Pre-reading (TOC, chapter summaries, headings), Active questioning while reading
Retention: Active recall (close book, write what you remember), Spaced repetition, Teaching others
Notes: Zettelkasten (atomic notes + connections), Cornell method (cues, notes, summary), Progressive summarization
Knowledge Management: PARA method (Projects, Areas, Resources, Archives), MOCs (Maps of Content), Tagging systems
Reading Strategy: Fiction (immersive, linear) vs. Nonfiction (strategic, non-linear, extract frameworks)

Best Practices
- Speed without comprehension is just eye movement — always test retention
- The Feynman Technique: If you can't explain it to a 12-year-old, you don't understand it
- Output > input — take notes, teach someone, write about what you read
- Not every book needs to be finished — quit bad books aggressively, life's too short
- Read the table of contents, introduction, and conclusion FIRST for nonfiction — then decide what chapters deserve deep reading

Common Actions
# Assessment
test_speed --passage provided --timer 1min --calculate WPM --test comprehension_5_questions
identify_habits --sub_vocalization check --regression check --fixation_time check

# Technique Training
practice_pacer --method finger_under_text --set_pace 120pct_current --duration 5min --gradually increase
reduce_sub_vocalization --technique "count 1-2-3-4 in your head while reading" --practice daily

# Knowledge Systems
setup_zettelkasten --tool Obsidian --structure atomic_notes links MOCs
apply_feynman --topic user_chosen --steps "explain simply → find gaps → re-study gaps → simplify again"

Pillar Mapping
Primary: 🌱 GROWTH
Sub-field: Learning
Synergies: Book Club Companion (reading list), Habit Coach (consistency), Productivity Architect (learning time)
